SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 695
By Oliver
A RESOLUTION to commend the Tennessee Justice Center on
the occasion of its thirtieth community birthday.
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly recognize those
outstanding Tennessee organizations that strive to promote equity and justice throughout their
communities and thereby improve the well-being of their fellow citizens; and
WHEREAS, one such organization is the Tennessee Justice Center, which marked its
thirtieth community birthday on February 4, 2026; and
WHEREAS, Tennessee Justice Center works to achieve opportunity, security, and
dignity for all Tennesseans and is committed to expanding and continuing its advocacy,
education, and litigation work as a means toward greater equity; and
WHEREAS, the goals of the organization are to help kids grow up healthy, ensure
access to affordable health care, increase independence among Tennessee's aging population,
and expand food security; and
WHEREAS, to date, the Tennessee Justice Center has secured $2.5 billion in
healthcare benefits and $300 million in food aid, assisting 95,000 children in acquiring Medicaid
services, 45,000 children and pregnant women in acquiring coverage, and 15,000 older
Tennesseans with at-home care; and
WHEREAS, for thirty years, Tennessee Justice Center has sought to advance
economic, racial, and social justice by relentlessly working for and with Tennesseans seeking
better lives for themselves and their neighbors, and it is our privilege to honor this venerable
organization on this special occasion; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
SJR0695
012820
- 1 -

REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we hereby commend the Tennessee Justice Center
on the occasion of its thirtieth community birthday, extending our best wishes for every
continued success.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
